WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.640
I hear we both lead data science teams.

00:00:13.640 --> 00:00:18.280
I specialize in getting data going at early stage startups.

00:00:18.280 --> 00:00:19.280
What do you do?

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:22.360
Basically, the same thing, but more in a larger organization.

00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:26.860
I develop data science teams, but taking it to the next level, trying to get them to be

00:00:26.860 --> 00:00:32.619
able to sustain their teams and be able to do their data and analytic architecture well.

00:00:32.619 --> 00:00:34.860
You know, that sounds great.

00:00:34.860 --> 00:00:39.660
Actually, getting data started from scratch, there are so many things that are frustrating.

00:00:39.660 --> 00:00:41.660
Often we kind of just run into a lot of barriers.

00:00:41.660 --> 00:00:45.740
It must be nice to be somewhere where everything is established and running smoothly.

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:48.220
You know, it would be nice.

00:00:48.220 --> 00:00:49.619
We have our challenges, too.

00:00:49.619 --> 00:00:53.220
Large organizations tend to be very slow, especially government organizations, and we

00:00:53.220 --> 00:00:56.099
tend to be more reactive than proactive.

00:00:56.099 --> 00:01:00.380
So we're leading to being able to change that to be more proactive in our organizations.

00:01:00.380 --> 00:01:04.019
You know, maybe I can share with you some of the things I've learned about getting data

00:01:04.019 --> 00:01:07.739
science off the ground, and then I would love to hear what you've learned about doing data

00:01:07.739 --> 00:01:08.739
science at scale.

00:01:08.739 --> 00:01:09.739
That'd be great.

00:01:09.739 --> 00:01:10.739
Thanks.

00:01:10.739 --> 00:01:17.260
So, I've thought a lot about what's kind of the root problem of some of these things that

00:01:17.260 --> 00:01:23.699
we face getting data science started or, you know, even the later stages, and what I've

00:01:23.699 --> 00:01:25.760
concluded is this.

00:01:25.760 --> 00:01:34.959
It's really that hope for data science is so high in terms of what we can deliver, but

00:01:34.959 --> 00:01:40.519
the understanding of how to set teams up for success is so low.

00:01:40.519 --> 00:01:45.400
And this can mean that your organization kind of accidentally makes it impossible for you

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:49.919
to do the job they were so excited to bring you in to do in the first place.

00:01:49.919 --> 00:01:55.239
So if you run into these problems, who can you turn to to help you kind of solve these

00:01:55.239 --> 00:01:58.400
organizational issues that you're facing?

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:02.360
And I think the answer is it's you.

00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:04.360
It's you, the data scientist.

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:06.800
It's us, the data scientists.

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:14.119
Maybe this shouldn't be our job, but in my experience, the best chance of success is

00:02:14.119 --> 00:02:20.919
if we take the lead in helping our organizations learn how to make us successful.

00:02:20.919 --> 00:02:25.119
So if we're going to do this, I think it's helpful to understand why we find ourselves

00:02:25.119 --> 00:02:29.880
in this situation where there's this big gap between the hope for what we can deliver and

00:02:29.880 --> 00:02:33.440
the understanding of how to help us do that.

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:35.399
So first of all, the hope part.

00:02:35.399 --> 00:02:40.559
If you put yourself in the mind of a CEO or another executive who decided to bring a data

00:02:40.559 --> 00:02:46.520
science team into an organization, these are the kinds of messages they're getting.

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:50.919
Data is the world's most valuable resource, right?

00:02:50.919 --> 00:02:57.800
So if you are someone who's in charge of the long-term strategic direction of an organization,

00:02:57.800 --> 00:03:01.600
you want to make sure you're not missing these big opportunities to be doing things with

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:03.220
data.

00:03:03.220 --> 00:03:06.600
And then I think on the flip side of that is fear.

00:03:06.639 --> 00:03:11.440
Most CEOs think their organizations have to evolve or die, whether they're small and early

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:14.039
stage or big and established.

00:03:14.039 --> 00:03:15.960
The world is changing quickly.

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:20.860
They need to stay on the cutting edge and be doing things that are transformative.

00:03:20.860 --> 00:03:24.500
And part of that is being smart about how they use data.

00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:29.639
So I think it's these big, high-level ideas that get people excited about what we can

00:03:29.639 --> 00:03:31.199
deliver.

00:03:32.199 --> 00:03:38.020
Years ago now, I was hired into a transit software company under these circumstances.

00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:43.600
The CEO was the one who decided that they needed to hire a data scientist.

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:48.600
And he told me, I know we have a lot of data, and I know there's more valuable things we

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:50.240
could be doing with it.

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:54.279
And I'm not sure exactly what that is, but we need you to help figure it out.

00:03:54.279 --> 00:03:58.479
So I went in knowing there was this uncertainty where I would have to help find the value

00:03:58.479 --> 00:04:01.940
in the data and help the company realize it.

00:04:01.940 --> 00:04:07.720
But I also knew I had the backing of the CEO, and so this seemed like a pretty good situation.

00:04:07.720 --> 00:04:12.559
So I arrived and started talking to the lead engineer about getting access to the data.

00:04:12.559 --> 00:04:18.239
And he said, oh, no, I can't give you access to the data.

00:04:18.239 --> 00:04:23.200
We've built our data pipelines with these particular needs for our production system,

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:25.500
and it's not built for analytic queries.

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:30.500
It's not safe for me to let you get the data.

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:32.380
So immediately, this is a problem, right?

00:04:32.380 --> 00:04:33.739
And so I had to keep pestering him.

00:04:33.739 --> 00:04:36.920
I can't do anything if you can't get me the data.

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:42.700
So eventually, he agreed, okay, we can try running a query so you can get some data.

00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:48.540
So I wrote the query, I checked with him, he approved it, and I sent it off.

00:04:48.540 --> 00:04:53.820
And I waited and waited, and it seemed like it was taking a really long time.

00:04:53.820 --> 00:04:57.880
So eventually, I wandered down the hall to ask him if he knew what was going on.

00:04:57.880 --> 00:05:04.019
And he was not available to talk to me, because he was in the middle of an emergency situation.

00:05:04.019 --> 00:05:09.119
All the buses in our product on the maps had stopped moving.

00:05:09.119 --> 00:05:10.660
And why had that happened?

00:05:10.660 --> 00:05:14.459
Of course, it was because of my one query.

00:05:14.459 --> 00:05:19.500
So that was the end for a long time of me getting access to that data.

00:05:19.500 --> 00:05:23.540
And this kind of, like, very basic problem is not unusual.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:26.019
I talk to other data scientists and data leaders.

00:05:26.019 --> 00:05:29.459
These are the kinds of things we face a lot.

00:05:29.459 --> 00:05:36.739
So there's three buckets of things, I think, that we need that organizations don't really

00:05:36.739 --> 00:05:39.420
understand coming in.

00:05:39.420 --> 00:05:42.019
One is analysis-ready data.

00:05:42.019 --> 00:05:44.779
And this can go wrong in several ways.

00:05:44.779 --> 00:05:50.339
One is you can't get access to the data, or it's not in a form that's safe for analytics.

00:05:50.339 --> 00:05:54.779
Another might be that the data you need for the project you're doing doesn't exist.

00:05:54.779 --> 00:05:56.899
Not really even being collected.

00:05:56.899 --> 00:06:01.380
Or maybe it is being collected, and you can get access to it, but the data management

00:06:01.380 --> 00:06:09.059
practices are so nonexistent that it's messy to the point where it's almost unusable.

00:06:09.059 --> 00:06:12.500
Another thing we need is cross-team support.

00:06:12.500 --> 00:06:17.299
So in the situation I was in at the transit company, the engineering team could have solved

00:06:17.299 --> 00:06:18.299
my problem.

00:06:18.299 --> 00:06:22.619
They had the ability to get the data into an analytics data warehouse, right?

00:06:22.619 --> 00:06:25.119
But they weren't expecting to need to do this work.

00:06:25.119 --> 00:06:28.600
No one realized the data scientists would need any support.

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:32.200
And they had a list of high-priority items that they were already struggling to be able

00:06:32.200 --> 00:06:34.519
to address with the capacity they had.

00:06:34.519 --> 00:06:37.359
So they weren't going to prioritize this.

00:06:37.359 --> 00:06:39.959
And this can also happen in the other direction.

00:06:39.959 --> 00:06:44.859
Sometimes people are thrilled to see you arrive as the data person, because they think,

00:06:44.859 --> 00:06:46.279
my team has data problems.

00:06:46.279 --> 00:06:48.519
We spend way too much time reporting.

00:06:48.519 --> 00:06:51.200
Here's someone who can solve this for us.

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:56.079
And then you can get a lot of incoming requests, which can be helpful in understanding what

00:06:56.079 --> 00:06:57.839
your organization needs.

00:06:57.839 --> 00:07:02.959
But if you can't control that, you end up spending all your time reacting to these requests,

00:07:02.959 --> 00:07:07.160
and never get to those potentially really high-impact projects, which are what people

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:12.079
really wanted data scientists for in the first place.

00:07:12.079 --> 00:07:15.320
And the third thing is space for uncertainty.

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:23.320
So unlike almost everything else that organizations do, data science projects depend on the contents

00:07:23.320 --> 00:07:26.959
of the data in a way that makes it hard to know whether they're worth doing until we've

00:07:26.959 --> 00:07:29.220
kind of already done them.

00:07:29.220 --> 00:07:34.200
And so this can make it really hard to fit into the normal way that your organization

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:37.920
plans work.

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:44.320
So if you find yourself dealing with these kinds of problems, what do you do?

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:49.720
And I think in my experience, there's a set of tactics that work here that I think of

00:07:49.720 --> 00:07:52.820
as guerrilla data science tactics.

00:07:52.820 --> 00:07:58.640
So this means maybe not doing things ideally the way that we should be doing them, but

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:01.760
doing what we have to do to make it work in the situation we're in.

00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:08.000
So being scrappy and clever and working around the obstacles in our way.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:13.920
But guerrilla, of course, comes from guerrilla warfare, and warfare is not the right mindset

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:16.000
for us to be in, right?

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.519
So as frustrated as we might get with some of our colleagues, they aren't trying to make

00:08:20.519 --> 00:08:22.119
things difficult for us.

00:08:22.119 --> 00:08:28.000
We're all wanting to make it work, we just haven't figured out how to do that yet.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:36.960
So instead, maybe we think about this as guerrilla data science, powerful but friendly.

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:41.559
So what does this actually mean in practice?

00:08:41.559 --> 00:08:46.919
There's a series of steps that I have found success with in getting data science off the

00:08:46.919 --> 00:08:48.400
ground.

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:51.940
The first step is scan for opportunity.

00:08:51.940 --> 00:08:58.380
So this means being heads up in your organization and looking for the overlap of what's valuable

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:03.020
to the organization and what you're able to do with data.

00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:09.520
And once you've found that opportunity, the next step is show, don't tell.

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:14.140
So it can be tempting to explain to people what you're thinking and what you're planning

00:09:14.140 --> 00:09:19.700
to do and what you need from them and how this is going to play out to get buy-in, but

00:09:19.820 --> 00:09:23.780
in my experience, at least early on, this is usually a waste of time.

00:09:23.780 --> 00:09:28.659
What you need to do is build the thing, at least the skinny version of the thing, so

00:09:28.659 --> 00:09:34.059
that they can see the vision you have in a more concrete way and have something to react

00:09:34.059 --> 00:09:36.099
to.

00:09:36.099 --> 00:09:40.099
Next, take the data and run.

00:09:40.099 --> 00:09:44.820
So this doesn't mean stealing the data or hacking into the data, but it means that if

00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:49.940
you can't get access in the way that you ultimately will need to, you have to do whatever

00:09:49.940 --> 00:09:52.719
it takes to get an initial data set.

00:09:52.719 --> 00:09:57.260
Maybe this means befriending an engineer who does have access and asking them to just help

00:09:57.260 --> 00:10:02.679
you get a one-time data set that you can get started with.

00:10:02.679 --> 00:10:09.619
And then once you've used that data set to build something that delivers on that opportunity,

00:10:09.619 --> 00:10:11.219
nail the landing.

00:10:11.219 --> 00:10:14.780
And what this means is communicate.

00:10:14.780 --> 00:10:20.020
So all of these things you've done up to this point don't matter if no one knows what you

00:10:20.020 --> 00:10:23.599
did or doesn't understand why it's valuable.

00:10:23.599 --> 00:10:28.979
And I think it's almost impossible to overinvest in communication, communicating things different

00:10:28.979 --> 00:10:34.539
ways until it connects with people and they really get it, and also communicating broadly.

00:10:34.539 --> 00:10:40.880
So not just your primary stakeholder or your team, but everyone around the organization.

00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:45.599
Make friends and talk to them all the time about what you're doing.

00:10:45.599 --> 00:10:49.599
And then once you've done this, it's time to up the ante.

00:10:49.599 --> 00:10:54.919
So once you've done an initial project that shows value and people know about it and understand

00:10:54.919 --> 00:11:01.159
it, you want to use that organizational goodwill to do something that's maybe higher risk but

00:11:01.159 --> 00:11:03.479
higher impact the next time.

00:11:03.479 --> 00:11:07.159
And so you go through this cycle again.

00:11:07.159 --> 00:11:12.119
So when I found myself in this position of not being able to access the data that I was

00:11:12.119 --> 00:11:18.000
there to find value in, I was at the scan for opportunity stage.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:22.799
And the opportunity that presented itself, we had just raised money, we had a growing

00:11:22.799 --> 00:11:27.500
employee base, people needed to understand what was going on with the company.

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:30.760
And so we worked on business metrics.

00:11:30.760 --> 00:11:35.200
Not what I had come to do, but it was the opportunity we had at the time.

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:39.640
And so we started building a FLEX dashboard and deployed it and were sharing it with people

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:42.679
so they could see what we were doing.

00:11:42.679 --> 00:11:46.960
The data here did not come from that production system, but we were able to find scrappy ways

00:11:46.960 --> 00:11:51.919
to pull information in from around the company to feed this dashboard.

00:11:51.919 --> 00:11:53.900
And then we communicated it to everyone.

00:11:53.900 --> 00:11:58.599
We showed it in company meetings, we talked to teams about how they could use it.

00:11:58.599 --> 00:12:02.179
And that got us some goodwill to do the next step.

00:12:02.179 --> 00:12:05.739
So now we're back to scan for opportunity.

00:12:05.739 --> 00:12:11.219
And this time, the company was getting into a new product in the area of microtransit,

00:12:11.219 --> 00:12:16.020
which is like an Uber pool for transit agencies and universities.

00:12:16.020 --> 00:12:17.700
And this runs on an algorithm.

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:23.619
So from our data science viewpoint, we thought, well, of course we understand how the algorithm

00:12:23.619 --> 00:12:28.380
works, but that's not the same as understanding how it will play out in the real world.

00:12:28.380 --> 00:12:32.419
And we thought we could figure that out, figure out where it works well and where it

00:12:32.419 --> 00:12:36.659
doesn't in which situations by using simulation.

00:12:36.659 --> 00:12:38.859
And so now we had this goodwill.

00:12:38.859 --> 00:12:40.940
So I thought, this time we can do it right.

00:12:40.940 --> 00:12:46.419
I went to the product manager and talked about our idea and why we thought it would be valuable

00:12:46.419 --> 00:12:49.840
and what we needed from the engineering teams to do this.

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:52.719
And she said, oh, that's interesting.

00:12:52.719 --> 00:12:54.859
We're not going to prioritize this.

00:12:54.859 --> 00:12:56.840
No one's asking me for it.

00:12:56.840 --> 00:13:01.359
We have a long list of high-priority items, and I already can't do them all with the team

00:13:01.359 --> 00:13:02.400
that I have.

00:13:02.400 --> 00:13:05.280
So we're just not going to be able to help you with this.

00:13:05.280 --> 00:13:08.140
So back to show, don't tell.

00:13:08.140 --> 00:13:14.200
How could we build a version of this that we could show people on our own?

00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:18.479
So in this case, because we were using simulation, we were creating our own data.

00:13:18.479 --> 00:13:20.599
So that's problem solved.

00:13:20.599 --> 00:13:23.359
But we still needed access to the algorithm.

00:13:23.359 --> 00:13:26.239
So we went to engineering with this one-time ask.

00:13:26.239 --> 00:13:30.719
Just help us get access so that we can run this algorithm offline.

00:13:30.719 --> 00:13:34.119
It won't interfere with your production system, and we'll leave you alone.

00:13:34.119 --> 00:13:36.179
And so we got that.

00:13:36.179 --> 00:13:38.919
So then we built our shiny app to create inputs.

00:13:38.919 --> 00:13:40.919
We scheduled all our simulations.

00:13:40.919 --> 00:13:44.320
We created reports for different scenarios.

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:46.760
So then we had something really cool to show people.

00:13:46.760 --> 00:13:50.880
So we went back to our team and the product manager and showed them this.

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:54.280
And within our department, people thought, you know, this is interesting,

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:55.840
but it's kind of like a toy.

00:13:55.840 --> 00:13:58.719
It's not really, you know, part of our software.

00:13:58.719 --> 00:14:01.200
It's just kind of an interesting side project.

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:02.359
But we kept talking about it.

00:14:02.359 --> 00:14:06.039
And one day, I showed it to the chief revenue officer.

00:14:06.039 --> 00:14:08.960
And he immediately saw the value in this because he's thinking

00:14:08.960 --> 00:14:10.559
about the customer, right?

00:14:10.559 --> 00:14:13.239
The customer is uncomfortable with this algorithm.

00:14:13.239 --> 00:14:16.159
They need to be able to see how this is going to work for them before they're

00:14:16.159 --> 00:14:18.000
willing to put this out in the world.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:22.239
And we very quickly became part of our marketing and sales process,

00:14:22.239 --> 00:14:26.119
and also part of how we communicated to our investors why this was important

00:14:26.119 --> 00:14:27.919
and what it actually was.

00:14:27.919 --> 00:14:31.799
So now we had gotten to that point of this high impact.

00:14:31.799 --> 00:14:35.599
This was the kind of thing that the CEO had wanted to bring the data science team

00:14:35.599 --> 00:14:37.599
in for to begin with.

00:14:40.719 --> 00:14:45.599
So a few reflections about what's important in this process.

00:14:45.599 --> 00:14:49.400
One is to maximize speed and autonomy.

00:14:49.400 --> 00:14:53.400
So even though we're in this privileged position where people have great faith

00:14:53.400 --> 00:14:55.719
that we can do amazing things, even though they don't quite know

00:14:55.719 --> 00:14:59.760
what they are, we still have to start delivering eventually, right?

00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:02.280
So we have a limited amount of time.

00:15:02.280 --> 00:15:06.719
And in my experience, the best way to maximize speed is to maximize

00:15:06.719 --> 00:15:09.000
autonomy of the team.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:14.239
And this doesn't mean working in a silo or not collaborating with other teams.

00:15:14.239 --> 00:15:17.799
But what it means to me is that that iterative data science

00:15:17.799 --> 00:15:22.840
development process, you need to be able to do that without running into places

00:15:22.840 --> 00:15:25.760
where you need help from another team, because that's what's going

00:15:25.760 --> 00:15:28.440
to slow you down.

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:32.559
The other thing is to build foundations wherever possible along the way.

00:15:32.559 --> 00:15:35.640
So even though we're doing these scrappy things in our guerrilla data

00:15:35.640 --> 00:15:39.799
science tactics, everywhere we have a chance, we want to start building things

00:15:39.799 --> 00:15:41.719
that we can build again on later.

00:15:41.719 --> 00:15:47.159
So building data pipelines that we can schedule, building R packages that we

00:15:47.159 --> 00:15:50.320
can reuse, all of those things.

00:15:50.320 --> 00:15:53.400
And these are the things where my teams have found PositConnect

00:15:53.400 --> 00:15:54.840
to be really helpful.

00:15:54.840 --> 00:15:59.320
So instead of every time we need to deploy a dashboard or we need to deploy

00:15:59.320 --> 00:16:03.799
an app or we need to run a cron job, having to go ask engineering for help

00:16:03.799 --> 00:16:07.200
with getting that set up, it was just a one-time ask,

00:16:07.200 --> 00:16:08.640
help us set up PositConnect.

00:16:08.640 --> 00:16:11.039
And then we're off and running on our own.

00:16:11.039 --> 00:16:14.440
And we can do all these things without constantly needing support.

00:16:17.520 --> 00:16:21.280
So if you've gone through this process and you've gotten to that first really

00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:24.799
high-impact result, pat yourself on the back.

00:16:24.799 --> 00:16:26.840
You can declare victory.

00:16:26.840 --> 00:16:30.960
And now you've completed step one, because this is just the beginning

00:16:30.960 --> 00:16:32.840
to create momentum.

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:38.400
But going forward, you can't do things this way and have a sustainable

00:16:38.400 --> 00:16:41.159
and scalable data science practice.

00:16:41.159 --> 00:16:46.320
Particularly the take the data and run step needs to evolve.

00:16:46.320 --> 00:16:49.760
And David, I would love to hear what you've learned about doing data science

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:52.200
at scale and how you've done some of these things.

00:16:52.200 --> 00:16:54.559
Happy to share.

00:16:54.559 --> 00:16:59.239
So, Elaine, when I was hearing you talk, it really brought back a lot of memories.

00:16:59.239 --> 00:17:03.440
I almost felt like I was in an episode of This Is My Life, because I went through

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:07.880
so many of these things similar to what you just did.

00:17:07.880 --> 00:17:10.760
And I just couldn't understand why it was so hard to get the data.

00:17:10.760 --> 00:17:15.400
I mean, it took me two years, two years to actually have the head of IT,

00:17:15.400 --> 00:17:20.920
of a human capital of IT, tell her staff, if David and his team need the data,

00:17:20.920 --> 00:17:22.760
they get the data.

00:17:22.760 --> 00:17:28.400
There was a lot of cajoling, a lot of begging, a lot of pulling hair out.

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:31.839
A lot of pulling hair out.

00:17:31.839 --> 00:17:36.040
But I think what really came down to was showing her that we could get answers

00:17:36.040 --> 00:17:41.599
in minutes instead of days or weeks at times.

00:17:41.599 --> 00:17:45.239
Let me give you a small example of our data access at that time when I first

00:17:45.239 --> 00:17:47.680
joined this organization.

00:17:47.680 --> 00:17:54.359
We had this personnel data warehouse where roughly 18,000 data employees were there

00:17:54.359 --> 00:17:58.119
in that information, all the data information about them.

00:17:58.119 --> 00:18:02.640
Now, I have to go to this web interface of this very well-known back-end database

00:18:02.640 --> 00:18:04.439
that we have to access.

00:18:04.439 --> 00:18:09.239
And there are some queries on there that I can pull that maybe have 10, 15,

00:18:09.239 --> 00:18:12.199
20 different attributes of an employee.

00:18:12.199 --> 00:18:15.760
It takes me maybe a minute to two minutes to have that thing load once I

00:18:15.760 --> 00:18:17.760
access that query.

00:18:17.760 --> 00:18:20.239
Then I have to add other attributes to that employee,

00:18:20.239 --> 00:18:22.640
depending on what I'm doing.

00:18:22.640 --> 00:18:25.800
That's another 10 to 30 seconds for each attribute.

00:18:25.800 --> 00:18:29.640
And if I got the wrong one because I don't have a data dictionary,

00:18:29.640 --> 00:18:31.079
I've got to pull that back.

00:18:31.079 --> 00:18:32.680
That's another 10 to 30 seconds.

00:18:32.680 --> 00:18:34.920
Add another one, another 10 to 30 seconds.

00:18:34.920 --> 00:18:38.760
Imagine doing that for 40, 50 different attributes.

00:18:38.760 --> 00:18:45.479
And I could only pull down 750,000 cells at one time.

00:18:45.479 --> 00:18:48.280
Not rows or observations, cells.

00:18:48.280 --> 00:18:52.959
And if I needed to do historical data 10 years back across all my centers,

00:18:52.959 --> 00:18:55.800
it could be days before I get all the data aligned.

00:18:55.800 --> 00:19:00.400
And please don't make a mistake because then I got to do it all over again.

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:01.640
So it was just amazing.

00:19:01.640 --> 00:19:03.599
Why can't I get to all this data?

00:19:03.599 --> 00:19:05.680
There had to be a better way.

00:19:05.680 --> 00:19:08.959
And there is, I think, I hope.

00:19:08.959 --> 00:19:12.119
So it takes a lot of information.

00:19:12.119 --> 00:19:16.560
It takes somebody that's going to take what you started and take it to the next

00:19:16.560 --> 00:19:21.119
level by advocating everything you've done and being able to talk to leaders and

00:19:21.119 --> 00:19:23.560
tell them this is why we need to do it.

00:19:23.560 --> 00:19:26.760
When we got to the end of our journey, which is very similar to yours,

00:19:26.760 --> 00:19:28.719
I thought I had built a mansion.

00:19:28.719 --> 00:19:30.959
I had all of these different applications out there that we could

00:19:30.959 --> 00:19:32.760
showcase things.

00:19:32.760 --> 00:19:35.920
But then really, did I really?

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:41.280
What I had was a facade with a bunch of little bitty trailers in the back.

00:19:41.280 --> 00:19:42.239
And they were nice trailers.

00:19:42.239 --> 00:19:42.839
Don't get me wrong.

00:19:42.839 --> 00:19:43.319
They were good.

00:19:43.319 --> 00:19:43.760
They worked.

00:19:43.760 --> 00:19:44.280
They worked well.

00:19:44.280 --> 00:19:45.359
They worked well together.

00:19:45.359 --> 00:19:48.839
But the individual little things all the time.

00:19:48.839 --> 00:19:54.520
There was no interface or any way for me to really share this across the enterprise.

00:19:54.560 --> 00:19:59.160
There wasn't any way for me to really get it out there and showcase it to the people.

00:19:59.160 --> 00:20:01.000
So we had to do something different.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:02.880
So what's next?

00:20:02.880 --> 00:20:05.479
Well, I started thinking about this, and it really all starts with the data,

00:20:05.479 --> 00:20:06.800
as Elaine had mentioned.

00:20:06.800 --> 00:20:08.800
The data is the key on everything we do.

00:20:08.800 --> 00:20:10.520
It is the oil, the next oil.

00:20:10.520 --> 00:20:14.079
It's our most vital commodity that we have.

00:20:14.079 --> 00:20:16.400
So you have to think about how you develop your data foundation,

00:20:16.400 --> 00:20:21.000
what you have to do to get that data from having to go grab it from somebody and

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:25.680
put it into a network to be able to get a pipeline that automatically gets it to you.

00:20:25.680 --> 00:20:29.160
But to do that, you have to set expectations with your leaders.

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:32.800
Because they'll come to you, you know, 10, 15 years ago it was,

00:20:32.800 --> 00:20:35.199
can you just do it like Google?

00:20:35.199 --> 00:20:38.560
Now it's, can you just make it like ChatGPT?

00:20:38.560 --> 00:20:40.040
It takes a while to do that.

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:44.359
I can't do that immediately because I don't, one, I don't have access to the data.

00:20:44.359 --> 00:20:46.160
And two, I don't want to see a whole lot of hallucinations,

00:20:46.160 --> 00:20:49.079
especially when we're trying to get back to the moon and onto Mars.

00:20:49.079 --> 00:20:52.280
We want to make sure we have this right.

00:20:52.280 --> 00:20:54.439
So I needed to create an understanding,

00:20:54.439 --> 00:20:58.760
level set the perceptions of everybody in the organization.

00:20:58.760 --> 00:21:04.040
But another key that I found was we need to differentiate between IT and data science.

00:21:04.040 --> 00:21:07.560
IT is the pipeline to get us the data.

00:21:07.560 --> 00:21:11.719
The data science, that's where we do the magic, as they so-called tell me,

00:21:11.719 --> 00:21:14.920
to be able to change things over and give them some kind of answers.

00:21:14.920 --> 00:21:17.319
So how do you do that?

00:21:17.359 --> 00:21:21.280
Well, several years ago I developed this, probably a little over a decade ago,

00:21:21.280 --> 00:21:24.439
I developed this framework that I call knowledge architecture.

00:21:24.439 --> 00:21:28.400
And let me give you a quick little story as to how this all derived and came up

00:21:28.400 --> 00:21:31.760
so you can understand what I'm trying to get to here.

00:21:31.760 --> 00:21:34.479
Again, over a decade ago I was leading a small team

00:21:34.479 --> 00:21:37.560
in a knowledge management group down at Johnson Space Center.

00:21:37.560 --> 00:21:41.040
And I was meeting with my taxonomist and my web developer.

00:21:41.040 --> 00:21:44.959
And we were talking over things and the taxonomist went to look at the web developer

00:21:44.959 --> 00:21:48.160
and she says, I need access to the metadata.

00:21:48.160 --> 00:21:51.400
And he, the web developer, adamantly said no.

00:21:51.400 --> 00:21:55.439
They went back and forth on this for 10, 15 minutes.

00:21:55.439 --> 00:21:58.479
I finally said, timeout guys, let's just go to respective corners,

00:21:58.479 --> 00:22:00.880
let's talk about this later.

00:22:00.880 --> 00:22:04.040
I went to go meet with my taxonomist separately,

00:22:04.040 --> 00:22:08.119
come to find out this conversation had been going on for a couple of months now

00:22:08.119 --> 00:22:10.760
and with no resolution.

00:22:10.760 --> 00:22:15.560
I said, first off, tell me, what's the definition of metadata?

00:22:15.560 --> 00:22:17.079
In her mind, the data on the data.

00:22:17.079 --> 00:22:18.239
Okay.

00:22:18.239 --> 00:22:20.760
Give me some examples.

00:22:20.760 --> 00:22:27.640
Author, abstract, date created, title, all information about the document

00:22:27.640 --> 00:22:32.680
that she was trying to categorize and classify in her system.

00:22:32.680 --> 00:22:36.760
Went to the web developer, had the same conversation.

00:22:36.760 --> 00:22:39.599
He gave me basically the same definition.

00:22:39.599 --> 00:22:40.560
All right.

00:22:40.560 --> 00:22:42.560
Give me some examples.

00:22:42.560 --> 00:22:46.640
Field type, length, size, anything you want to talk about a database,

00:22:46.640 --> 00:22:48.040
what's that information?

00:22:48.040 --> 00:22:53.280
Again, level setting the organization to have them communicate.

00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:56.280
Same definition, different examples.

00:22:56.280 --> 00:22:58.640
Once I got them talking on the same way, they were able to get

00:22:58.640 --> 00:23:00.520
that information to them.

00:23:00.520 --> 00:23:04.880
So, it was really more about understanding each other's world to be able to do that.

00:23:04.880 --> 00:23:07.920
So, that's when I started thinking, we need a liaison, we need a group.

00:23:07.920 --> 00:23:09.680
And that's where knowledge architecture came into play.

00:23:09.680 --> 00:23:14.400
It's somebody that can talk all three languages to get this information across.

00:23:14.400 --> 00:23:16.479
So, what is knowledge architecture?

00:23:16.479 --> 00:23:17.920
This is my mind.

00:23:17.920 --> 00:23:21.079
Knowledge architecture is a combination of knowledge management,

00:23:21.079 --> 00:23:24.479
informatics, and data science.

00:23:24.479 --> 00:23:30.040
Knowledge management is a strategy for how we identify, store, analyze,

00:23:30.040 --> 00:23:33.160
and visualize our information, our data.

00:23:33.160 --> 00:23:35.920
Informatics, again, is that pipeline.

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:38.760
They're the ones that get that data, get our commodity,

00:23:38.760 --> 00:23:42.400
our oil from one place through the processing.

00:23:42.400 --> 00:23:45.880
In order for us to get it out there, we can utilize it.

00:23:45.880 --> 00:23:49.160
And then data science is the algorithms and methodologies we use to turn that data

00:23:49.160 --> 00:23:51.920
into some kind of actionable knowledge.

00:23:51.920 --> 00:23:58.599
And by doing that and combining all of that, we start to develop our data foundation.

00:23:58.599 --> 00:24:01.400
I've set some expectations, I'm communicating across,

00:24:01.400 --> 00:24:06.040
I've created that understanding, and I'm differentiating what's between IT and data.

00:24:06.040 --> 00:24:08.400
That gets me started to develop this framework

00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:13.319
that we can start creating those data analytical pipelines that allow us

00:24:13.319 --> 00:24:17.959
to more efficiently use our data in our organization.

00:24:17.959 --> 00:24:20.000
So, I started this again.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:22.479
It all starts with the data.

00:24:22.479 --> 00:24:26.599
Think back if you've seen Raiders of the Lost Ark in the last scene

00:24:26.599 --> 00:24:29.280
where they're taking that ark and putting it into a warehouse and it's going back

00:24:29.280 --> 00:24:32.000
and you don't see it again for forever.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:33.319
That's kind of how we've done our data.

00:24:33.319 --> 00:24:35.680
NASA's been around for 60 plus years.

00:24:35.680 --> 00:24:38.400
We've stored a lot of data and it's just kind of sitting there somewhere.

00:24:38.400 --> 00:24:42.560
And it first started in filing cabinets, then it went to file servers,

00:24:42.560 --> 00:24:47.400
then to SharePoint, databases, all in the same structure.

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:52.199
We've always collected the data just to store it.

00:24:52.199 --> 00:24:54.920
And that's basically it.

00:24:54.920 --> 00:24:56.160
We need to do better.

00:24:56.160 --> 00:25:00.079
I think you talked about it as analysis ready data.

00:25:00.079 --> 00:25:00.800
We need data.

00:25:00.800 --> 00:25:03.760
We need to collect data with analysis in mind.

00:25:03.760 --> 00:25:07.239
We need curated AIML ready data sets.

00:25:07.239 --> 00:25:09.439
And that will support us.

00:25:09.439 --> 00:25:13.560
No more of this takes me 80% of my time to clean the data in order

00:25:13.560 --> 00:25:14.920
for me to do my analysis.

00:25:14.920 --> 00:25:18.199
I want to get to the data and start working and doing the analysis.

00:25:18.199 --> 00:25:22.319
So, some of the things we need to do when we look at that is we think

00:25:22.319 --> 00:25:25.160
about our orchestration and ingestion.

00:25:25.239 --> 00:25:28.680
And this comes by working with IT and differentiating that.

00:25:28.680 --> 00:25:33.800
So, it will take somebody as to lead this effort.

00:25:33.800 --> 00:25:38.880
Somebody like a chief analytics officer, somebody that's going to work

00:25:38.880 --> 00:25:41.520
with the senior leaders in order to show this is the difference

00:25:41.520 --> 00:25:43.319
of why we need to do this.

00:25:43.319 --> 00:25:46.880
Too many times we put analytics into IT.

00:25:46.880 --> 00:25:51.560
Yes, data science is code, but we're not IT developers.

00:25:51.560 --> 00:25:52.439
We do our own thing.

00:25:52.439 --> 00:25:54.599
We have ways of doing things that we need to differentiate

00:25:54.599 --> 00:25:57.160
between the IT and data science life cycle.

00:25:57.160 --> 00:25:58.640
So, we need to make sure we get that done.

00:25:58.640 --> 00:26:01.319
So, how we're going to ingest from our data sources

00:26:01.319 --> 00:26:03.119
into various different things.

00:26:03.119 --> 00:26:05.920
So, we want to take my personnel data warehouse.

00:26:05.920 --> 00:26:08.719
What I'm kind of doing right now is taking my data from my personnel data

00:26:08.719 --> 00:26:12.439
warehouse based on the types of analysis that we need to do

00:26:12.439 --> 00:26:16.040
in creating these AIML curated data sets.

00:26:16.040 --> 00:26:18.199
So, we're taking it through those systems.

00:26:18.199 --> 00:26:19.880
We're transforming it.

00:26:19.880 --> 00:26:21.280
And I'll talk a little bit about that in a minute.

00:26:21.280 --> 00:26:25.560
But we're getting to the point where it's ready for us to be able to use it.

00:26:25.560 --> 00:26:29.839
But you also have to make sure that somebody's talking to IT security.

00:26:29.839 --> 00:26:33.760
Again, if you're in a large organization like NASA, we've been around many years.

00:26:33.760 --> 00:26:36.800
We've been around before there was a network.

00:26:36.800 --> 00:26:40.719
I went through the Cisco versus Novell phase of who's going to end

00:26:40.719 --> 00:26:43.880
up being the networking organizations.

00:26:43.880 --> 00:26:45.920
But each center did their own way.

00:26:45.920 --> 00:26:47.920
We have these firewalls that are all over the place.

00:26:47.920 --> 00:26:51.719
So, if you don't talk to IT security early, you're going to be stopped

00:26:51.719 --> 00:26:52.959
in your tracks very quickly.

00:26:52.959 --> 00:26:55.040
So, you got to make sure you get them involved.

00:26:55.040 --> 00:26:57.160
They can be a headache sometimes.

00:26:57.160 --> 00:26:59.880
But it's well worth it to get in there and talk to them to make sure

00:26:59.880 --> 00:27:04.239
that they understand why you need access to data and how to get to that data.

00:27:04.239 --> 00:27:06.439
But here's the key in my mind.

00:27:06.439 --> 00:27:09.439
You need to work with the data owners and the data stewards

00:27:09.439 --> 00:27:14.119
to get them to understand their role in the organization.

00:27:14.119 --> 00:27:16.560
Too many times, the data owner, and these are the people

00:27:16.560 --> 00:27:18.760
that run the business side.

00:27:18.760 --> 00:27:22.800
The person that actually owns the data for that business process.

00:27:22.800 --> 00:27:26.040
Or the person that's a data steward that understands the processes

00:27:26.040 --> 00:27:27.680
for how that data goes through.

00:27:27.680 --> 00:27:29.560
They need to understand their responsibility.

00:27:29.560 --> 00:27:33.079
Too many times, they've given up those responsibilities to IT.

00:27:33.079 --> 00:27:35.640
No, IT doesn't own the data.

00:27:35.640 --> 00:27:36.800
They get it to you.

00:27:36.800 --> 00:27:37.680
The data owners own it.

00:27:37.680 --> 00:27:40.239
So, you got to make sure they understand what they need to do.

00:27:40.239 --> 00:27:41.640
Get them involved.

00:27:41.640 --> 00:27:45.839
Show them the value, as Elaine said, of if we use your data correctly,

00:27:45.839 --> 00:27:48.319
this is what we can do for you guys.

00:27:48.319 --> 00:27:54.319
And then that leads us, again, it's, we as data scientists may not,

00:27:54.319 --> 00:27:56.079
it may not necessarily be our role, but we have to take it

00:27:56.079 --> 00:27:58.199
on because nobody else is doing it right now.

00:27:58.199 --> 00:28:01.800
We have to advocate for data literacy and data governance.

00:28:01.800 --> 00:28:03.119
We have to get people to understand.

00:28:03.119 --> 00:28:05.560
Everybody in the organization should be somewhat data literate

00:28:05.560 --> 00:28:08.599
so they can help us help them.

00:28:08.599 --> 00:28:12.839
And by data literacy, the ability to read, work with,

00:28:12.839 --> 00:28:15.079
analyze, or communicate with data.

00:28:15.079 --> 00:28:18.920
Whatever their role is, whether that's a project manager,

00:28:18.920 --> 00:28:21.359
administrator, or anything, they all need to know how to work

00:28:21.359 --> 00:28:23.359
with their data, and that helps us help them.

00:28:23.359 --> 00:28:25.319
So, we've got to advocate for these types of things

00:28:25.319 --> 00:28:28.920
in an organization to really raise the level of what we're trying

00:28:28.920 --> 00:28:31.599
to do and make it sustainable.

00:28:31.599 --> 00:28:34.520
So, how do we create a sustainable pipeline?

00:28:34.520 --> 00:28:37.560
How do we get to where we get our old data sources,

00:28:37.560 --> 00:28:42.959
it goes through some data sources into our data lake, or our data mesh,

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:47.199
or our data water fountain, or whatever we want to call it.

00:28:47.199 --> 00:28:50.959
It's all there and able to be shared and visualized.

00:28:50.959 --> 00:28:55.040
So, before I get there, I'm going to give you another quick story.

00:28:55.040 --> 00:28:58.640
I talked earlier about how I got the data and how it took me

00:28:58.640 --> 00:29:01.520
so long to get that data.

00:29:01.520 --> 00:29:04.719
Well, I didn't tell you the next part of this pipeline.

00:29:04.719 --> 00:29:07.839
Once I got that query built, a little button up there

00:29:07.839 --> 00:29:10.920
that says download CSV file.

00:29:10.920 --> 00:29:13.560
Okay. I download the CSV file.

00:29:13.560 --> 00:29:18.040
Maybe one file, maybe 10, 20, 30 files I have to download.

00:29:18.040 --> 00:29:21.560
Then I put that on my laptop, and on my laptop,

00:29:21.560 --> 00:29:25.839
I open up our studio, VS Code, Tableau, whatever we're using

00:29:25.839 --> 00:29:27.280
to ingest the data, start working,

00:29:27.280 --> 00:29:30.160
and start doing our visualization, our analysis, and do that.

00:29:30.160 --> 00:29:33.199
And I create these great applications.

00:29:33.199 --> 00:29:36.439
We create these great dashboards.

00:29:36.439 --> 00:29:38.719
Then it comes time to present it.

00:29:38.719 --> 00:29:39.920
So, here I go.

00:29:39.920 --> 00:29:43.680
Take my laptop, go to one meeting, plug it in,

00:29:43.680 --> 00:29:44.959
show if this is what we're doing.

00:29:44.959 --> 00:29:47.760
Like that guy, go to the next meeting, show it again,

00:29:47.760 --> 00:29:49.199
go to the next meeting, show it again.

00:29:49.199 --> 00:29:50.520
Oh, you want to change?

00:29:50.520 --> 00:29:52.319
Hold on. There you go.

00:29:52.319 --> 00:29:53.800
That was our pipeline.

00:29:53.800 --> 00:29:55.880
That's what we had to do.

00:29:55.880 --> 00:29:59.239
You know, no, no, we can do better than this.

00:29:59.239 --> 00:30:01.359
We have to do better than this.

00:30:01.359 --> 00:30:02.839
So, how do we do this?

00:30:02.839 --> 00:30:05.920
Well, we do have to think about ingestion.

00:30:05.920 --> 00:30:09.160
And that ingestion requires us to be able to turn our data,

00:30:09.160 --> 00:30:11.640
as we're taking it out of our raw data set,

00:30:11.640 --> 00:30:13.640
of my personnel data warehouse.

00:30:13.640 --> 00:30:16.520
I've got to use my scripts, use my containers,

00:30:16.520 --> 00:30:19.400
use whatever I need to do, however my pipeline's set up,

00:30:19.400 --> 00:30:22.719
to take that from a raw data set,

00:30:22.719 --> 00:30:24.280
and then turn it into a trusted data set.

00:30:24.280 --> 00:30:26.439
So, it comes into my data lake.

00:30:26.439 --> 00:30:31.000
That's my trusted data set for my data scientists.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:33.199
Then we start curating it.

00:30:33.199 --> 00:30:38.319
Let's say it's something on demographics of my employees.

00:30:38.319 --> 00:30:40.119
So, I've created this demographic data set.

00:30:40.119 --> 00:30:41.319
Then I start curating it.

00:30:41.319 --> 00:30:43.560
I break out the columns I need to break out,

00:30:43.560 --> 00:30:46.479
get it all ready so that it's ready for analysis.

00:30:46.479 --> 00:30:49.959
And that data set gets updated on a regular basis.

00:30:49.959 --> 00:30:52.040
And that data set is what my data scientists use

00:30:52.040 --> 00:30:55.800
for any and all demographic analysis.

00:30:55.800 --> 00:30:58.239
We've created data dictionaries, data glossaries,

00:30:58.239 --> 00:31:00.239
so everybody knows how the calculation goes

00:31:00.239 --> 00:31:01.119
and how to utilize it.

00:31:01.119 --> 00:31:03.640
We've created wikis to share that information.

00:31:03.640 --> 00:31:06.479
So, all of that's there so that everybody's using

00:31:06.479 --> 00:31:08.479
the same data set.

00:31:08.479 --> 00:31:10.079
Because in the previous way,

00:31:10.079 --> 00:31:12.479
with that downloaded from the web,

00:31:12.479 --> 00:31:14.839
I may pull some data, somebody else will pull some data,

00:31:14.839 --> 00:31:16.479
somebody else pulls some data,

00:31:16.479 --> 00:31:19.160
we probably don't have the same results

00:31:19.160 --> 00:31:21.520
because we're all pulling it on different days,

00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:23.199
or maybe we had different fields.

00:31:23.199 --> 00:31:24.040
This way we're saying,

00:31:24.040 --> 00:31:26.760
this is the data set you're using for demographics.

00:31:26.760 --> 00:31:31.319
And that goes into our, as a curated data set.

00:31:31.319 --> 00:31:33.640
And then that curated data set can then be used

00:31:33.640 --> 00:31:35.680
to share it across the organization

00:31:35.680 --> 00:31:37.719
for analysis visualizations internally

00:31:37.719 --> 00:31:39.479
and externally across the organization.

00:31:39.479 --> 00:31:41.319
That all fits into our pipeline.

00:31:41.319 --> 00:31:44.479
So, you got raw, trusted, curated, shared.

00:31:44.479 --> 00:31:47.000
But you have to have an understanding of your storage.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:48.400
How are you going to store it?

00:31:48.400 --> 00:31:49.439
What are you going to do with it?

00:31:49.439 --> 00:31:52.000
What type of systems are you going to use for storage?

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:54.000
And then from that, you have the integration piece.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:56.119
How do you access that storage?

00:31:56.119 --> 00:31:58.560
APIs, direct access, ODBC,

00:31:58.560 --> 00:32:01.680
what are you going to use to access that type of information?

00:32:01.680 --> 00:32:03.839
Then how are you going to analyze it,

00:32:03.839 --> 00:32:05.040
and then eventually present it?

00:32:05.040 --> 00:32:07.280
So, the way I usually talk to my organizations

00:32:07.280 --> 00:32:10.400
or my managers, you want me to present you some information?

00:32:10.400 --> 00:32:12.920
You want me to visualize this for you?

00:32:12.920 --> 00:32:15.040
I have to be able to analyze it.

00:32:15.040 --> 00:32:16.640
In order for me to analyze it,

00:32:16.640 --> 00:32:18.400
I have to be able to integrate with that.

00:32:18.400 --> 00:32:19.640
I have to be able to connect to it.

00:32:19.640 --> 00:32:22.280
I have to be able to access it with the right permissions.

00:32:22.280 --> 00:32:23.599
In order for me to be able to do that,

00:32:23.599 --> 00:32:25.839
I have to know where it's stored and how it's stored.

00:32:25.839 --> 00:32:28.359
I've got probably 30, 40, 50 different databases out there

00:32:28.359 --> 00:32:29.920
I have to keep an eye on and track on

00:32:29.920 --> 00:32:32.800
and see where we're getting the various data from.

00:32:32.800 --> 00:32:35.439
So, there's a lot of things you have to do.

00:32:35.439 --> 00:32:37.239
But that's why when they say,

00:32:37.239 --> 00:32:39.640
can't you just do it like chat GPT or do it?

00:32:39.640 --> 00:32:41.880
This is what it takes for me to do that.

00:32:41.880 --> 00:32:42.959
In order for me to do that,

00:32:42.959 --> 00:32:44.079
you've got to give me the funding,

00:32:44.079 --> 00:32:45.160
you've got to give me the authority,

00:32:45.160 --> 00:32:47.199
you've got to give me the access to do that.

00:32:47.199 --> 00:32:50.000
Once they see that, they start to say,

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.400
great, you can do that, let's go forward.

00:32:52.400 --> 00:32:53.839
And they're starting to get this information

00:32:53.839 --> 00:32:55.680
quicker and faster.

00:32:56.520 --> 00:32:57.359
And we can do it on the fly,

00:32:57.359 --> 00:32:58.680
then they're starting to see the value

00:32:58.680 --> 00:32:59.800
of what we're really trying to do.

00:32:59.800 --> 00:33:02.439
And they're starting to say, we want more of that.

00:33:02.439 --> 00:33:04.119
And once they get hooked on that,

00:33:04.119 --> 00:33:05.760
they really want to see that information

00:33:05.760 --> 00:33:07.479
because I keep trying to tell them,

00:33:07.479 --> 00:33:11.239
and probably one I didn't emphasize enough,

00:33:11.239 --> 00:33:13.359
and you do need an advocate.

00:33:13.359 --> 00:33:16.760
I'm constantly going to meetings and talking about this.

00:33:16.760 --> 00:33:19.560
Somebody has to be there to keep telling them

00:33:19.560 --> 00:33:23.160
why they need this because if you don't, they'll forget.

00:33:23.160 --> 00:33:25.640
Because management changes, new people come in,

00:33:26.479 --> 00:33:28.199
you've got to go back and tell the story all over again.

00:33:28.199 --> 00:33:29.800
You've got to be able to do that

00:33:29.800 --> 00:33:31.560
and be able to consistently do that

00:33:31.560 --> 00:33:33.479
and share those stories with you.

00:33:33.479 --> 00:33:35.880
So, once you have all of that,

00:33:35.880 --> 00:33:37.199
you may end up something like this.

00:33:37.199 --> 00:33:39.439
Now, the one on the left, the little diagram there,

00:33:39.439 --> 00:33:41.400
it's just something I created that I go,

00:33:41.400 --> 00:33:44.359
and this is actually animated and integrated

00:33:44.359 --> 00:33:46.319
and I can dynamic links and things

00:33:46.319 --> 00:33:47.640
that I can show to my managers

00:33:47.640 --> 00:33:49.880
to show all the different pieces that we have.

00:33:49.880 --> 00:33:52.800
But my analytic architecture first starts with the people.

00:33:52.800 --> 00:33:55.479
Understand what type of users you have,

00:33:56.319 --> 00:33:57.560
both the end users, your data scientists,

00:33:57.560 --> 00:33:59.359
your business intelligence analysts,

00:33:59.359 --> 00:34:00.199
all of the different people

00:34:00.199 --> 00:34:01.959
that are going to be using the data.

00:34:01.959 --> 00:34:02.800
Then you work through,

00:34:02.800 --> 00:34:04.479
how do you create that data pipeline?

00:34:04.479 --> 00:34:05.760
What are you going to use for that?

00:34:05.760 --> 00:34:07.079
Are you going through what types

00:34:07.079 --> 00:34:09.800
of different codes, mechanisms, repositories

00:34:09.800 --> 00:34:13.439
just to share the documents and the code configuration?

00:34:13.439 --> 00:34:14.399
How are you going to store it

00:34:14.399 --> 00:34:16.919
in some kind of container on a repos?

00:34:16.919 --> 00:34:18.080
Again, how are you going to integrate

00:34:18.080 --> 00:34:19.479
with that data on number four?

00:34:19.479 --> 00:34:21.439
Again, what type of APIs?

00:34:21.439 --> 00:34:24.560
And this is another thing I just thought of, APIs.

00:34:24.600 --> 00:34:27.719
Talking to my IT guy who's creating all these APIs for me,

00:34:28.879 --> 00:34:30.320
finally figured out we have a difference

00:34:30.320 --> 00:34:33.080
in what we need APIs for.

00:34:33.080 --> 00:34:36.239
Again, same definition, different use.

00:34:36.239 --> 00:34:40.000
They're using APIs to pull data

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:42.760
and put it on a website, on a web browser.

00:34:42.760 --> 00:34:45.800
They need one, maybe two data sets

00:34:45.800 --> 00:34:48.600
or two fields or observations coming through there.

00:34:48.600 --> 00:34:51.000
I need APIs that's going to pull

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:53.959
massive amount of data over to my storage.

00:34:53.959 --> 00:34:55.439
Again, doing the same thing

00:34:55.439 --> 00:34:57.360
but just costs us different resources.

00:34:57.360 --> 00:35:00.600
And I have slowed and broken a lot of servers

00:35:00.600 --> 00:35:02.760
over my years doing these types of things.

00:35:02.760 --> 00:35:04.560
So I have to really talk to my IT about

00:35:04.560 --> 00:35:07.520
how do we set these APIs up and what we're trying to do.

00:35:07.520 --> 00:35:08.959
So those are things you have to consider

00:35:08.959 --> 00:35:10.520
when you're doing these things.

00:35:10.520 --> 00:35:12.000
Then you have to look at your data sources

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:14.360
and understand what are the different types of connections.

00:35:14.360 --> 00:35:15.800
We have a lot of different databases

00:35:15.800 --> 00:35:17.719
but we don't have all of the modules

00:35:17.719 --> 00:35:19.879
that those databases may need.

00:35:19.879 --> 00:35:21.479
We don't have all of the connectivity

00:35:21.479 --> 00:35:23.320
to some of those databases.

00:35:23.320 --> 00:35:26.719
Sometimes they give us access or we can do read access.

00:35:26.719 --> 00:35:27.800
Sometimes we don't.

00:35:27.800 --> 00:35:29.520
So there's a lot of things you have to work through

00:35:29.520 --> 00:35:31.479
and try to get there.

00:35:31.479 --> 00:35:34.360
I mean, it's difficult but it's well worth

00:35:34.360 --> 00:35:36.399
somebody getting in there and trying to work with them

00:35:36.399 --> 00:35:38.120
to take this done.

00:35:38.120 --> 00:35:39.399
Then you can start thinking about

00:35:39.399 --> 00:35:41.800
how are you going to store that into a data lake

00:35:41.800 --> 00:35:44.040
and get your curated data sets.

00:35:44.040 --> 00:35:47.000
And then the fun really starts for a data scientist.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:49.399
How do we start turning that into some kind of

00:35:49.399 --> 00:35:51.760
visualization application or something?

00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:53.879
It could be some kind of no-code or low-code tool

00:35:53.879 --> 00:35:56.120
like Alteryx KNIME or something like that.

00:35:56.120 --> 00:35:57.760
Or something where we're using more high-code

00:35:57.760 --> 00:36:00.800
and ML DevOps with our POSIX servers.

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:03.560
We've got Vetiver that helps us with some of our modeling.

00:36:03.560 --> 00:36:06.159
We've got different things or MLflow or Kubeflow.

00:36:06.159 --> 00:36:07.159
There's a lot of different things

00:36:07.159 --> 00:36:09.719
but that gives us opportunity to do so many things.

00:36:09.719 --> 00:36:11.760
And my team is both Python and R

00:36:11.760 --> 00:36:12.639
and we can do a lot of that

00:36:12.639 --> 00:36:14.919
within those ecosystems right now.

00:36:14.919 --> 00:36:16.439
Then you've got your business intelligence.

00:36:16.439 --> 00:36:18.399
How are you going to present it out there?

00:36:18.399 --> 00:36:20.000
Tableau, Power BI.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:22.320
Again, you can do that in Shiny.

00:36:22.320 --> 00:36:25.239
Or then building some kind of analytical application.

00:36:25.239 --> 00:36:28.000
But the one key is always, always, always

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:30.040
have a group doing some kind of research

00:36:30.040 --> 00:36:32.520
on the next technologies that are coming out there.

00:36:32.520 --> 00:36:33.899
Because if you're not keeping up to date

00:36:33.899 --> 00:36:36.219
or at least understanding what's going on,

00:36:36.219 --> 00:36:37.439
you're going to be two years behind

00:36:37.439 --> 00:36:39.760
by the time you decide it's time for me to move.

00:36:39.760 --> 00:36:42.179
So you need to make sure you research as well as you can

00:36:42.179 --> 00:36:43.479
to make sure that thing,

00:36:43.479 --> 00:36:46.239
you've got some kind of momentum going

00:36:46.239 --> 00:36:47.399
so when the managers ask you,

00:36:47.399 --> 00:36:48.320
your executive leaders ask you

00:36:48.320 --> 00:36:49.800
what's the next thing you need to do,

00:36:50.600 --> 00:36:52.760
you're ready to go because you've done your research.

00:36:52.760 --> 00:36:56.979
So, that should hopefully take you from data confusion

00:36:56.979 --> 00:36:59.580
where you get your Lego spread all over the place

00:36:59.580 --> 00:37:02.040
to data intelligence where you use your algorithms,

00:37:02.040 --> 00:37:03.360
your methodologies to create

00:37:03.360 --> 00:37:05.239
some kind of actionable knowledge.

00:37:05.239 --> 00:37:07.120
Something that's useful for your organization

00:37:07.120 --> 00:37:08.679
through that process.

00:37:08.679 --> 00:37:11.000
So it's kind of a little visualization there

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:14.600
that some managers really like to see it, they get it.

00:37:14.600 --> 00:37:16.439
They like those pictures.

00:37:16.439 --> 00:37:17.280
You know, for some reason.

00:37:17.280 --> 00:37:19.159
And this helps them understand why it's important

00:37:19.520 --> 00:37:22.080
for us to get from one level to the other.

00:37:22.080 --> 00:37:23.639
So I think Elaine has said it earlier,

00:37:23.639 --> 00:37:25.340
hopefully we've stuck the landing.

00:37:26.719 --> 00:37:28.679
And that's my story.

00:37:28.679 --> 00:37:30.639
That was so helpful to hear.

00:37:30.639 --> 00:37:31.479
Thank you.

00:37:31.479 --> 00:37:36.479
You know, I'm still stuck on that part at the beginning

00:37:39.939 --> 00:37:43.179
about two years to get access to the data.

00:37:43.179 --> 00:37:44.840
But that's a really good reminder for me

00:37:44.840 --> 00:37:47.560
that patience and persistence can pay off in the end.

00:37:47.840 --> 00:37:48.679
That is true.

00:37:48.679 --> 00:37:51.760
And it really, for me, it was really validation

00:37:51.760 --> 00:37:55.040
that knowing that others have suffered along with me

00:37:55.040 --> 00:37:55.879
or are suffering along with me

00:37:55.879 --> 00:37:57.080
with the journeys they're taking,

00:37:57.080 --> 00:37:59.439
but realize that it is worth it in the end

00:37:59.439 --> 00:38:01.959
to continue on the perseverance that you're doing.

00:38:03.399 --> 00:38:04.919
Thank you very much, everybody.

00:38:04.919 --> 00:38:05.760
Thank you.

00:38:05.760 --> 00:38:06.580
Thank you.

00:38:06.580 --> 00:38:07.419
Thank you.

00:38:07.419 --> 00:38:08.260
Thank you.

00:38:08.260 --> 00:38:09.080
Thank you.

00:38:09.080 --> 00:38:09.919
Thank you.

00:38:09.919 --> 00:38:10.760
Thank you.

00:38:10.760 --> 00:38:11.580
Thank you.

00:38:11.580 --> 00:38:12.419
Thank you.

00:38:12.419 --> 00:38:14.239
Thank you so much, David and Elaine,

00:38:14.239 --> 00:38:15.679
for joining us here today.

00:38:15.679 --> 00:38:19.040
And I'm so happy that you both got to meet here in person

00:38:19.040 --> 00:38:22.739
and that so many of us get to meet this week.

00:38:22.739 --> 00:38:24.879
Feel free to take a seat for the Q&A.

00:38:28.199 --> 00:38:29.239
I'm Rachel Dempsey.

00:38:29.239 --> 00:38:32.600
I lead our customer marketing here at Posit

00:38:32.600 --> 00:38:35.419
and host our weekly data science hangout

00:38:35.419 --> 00:38:38.719
where you may have met Elaine or David there.

00:38:39.800 --> 00:38:41.679
We'd like to open up this opportunity

00:38:41.679 --> 00:38:44.520
to ask some questions to Elaine and David.

00:38:44.520 --> 00:38:47.760
And so you'll see on the screen here,

00:38:47.760 --> 00:38:50.840
you can use that short link to go over to Slido.

00:38:51.719 --> 00:38:53.080
I know we're not gonna have time

00:38:53.080 --> 00:38:55.520
for every single great question right now.

00:38:55.520 --> 00:38:59.280
So David and Elaine are also gonna join me in the lounge

00:38:59.280 --> 00:39:02.100
right next door, right after this too.

00:39:03.919 --> 00:39:06.040
And so I'll get things kicked off

00:39:06.040 --> 00:39:09.280
and thank you Hadley for helping gather questions for me.

00:39:10.199 --> 00:39:13.280
But Elaine, you mentioned it's almost impossible

00:39:13.280 --> 00:39:16.040
to over invest in communication.

00:39:16.040 --> 00:39:18.939
And I was wondering what has helped you most

00:39:18.939 --> 00:39:21.979
in getting people to grasp what you're saying with data?

00:39:23.639 --> 00:39:26.360
Yeah, I think we struggle with this sometimes

00:39:26.360 --> 00:39:29.060
as data scientists because spending a lot of time

00:39:29.060 --> 00:39:31.600
figuring this out doesn't feel like the work

00:39:31.600 --> 00:39:33.760
we're supposed to be doing.

00:39:33.760 --> 00:39:38.760
But what I found really helpful is trying to get inside

00:39:38.760 --> 00:39:41.000
the head of the audience, whoever that is.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:42.840
So if you're presenting to the CEO,

00:39:43.239 --> 00:39:45.040
that's one perspective.

00:39:45.040 --> 00:39:46.300
If you're presenting to IT,

00:39:46.300 --> 00:39:48.399
that's a completely different perspective.

00:39:49.679 --> 00:39:51.719
But I think usually when we start thinking about

00:39:51.719 --> 00:39:54.040
how to present work we've done ourselves,

00:39:54.040 --> 00:39:56.000
we're really in the process,

00:39:56.000 --> 00:40:00.439
like we tend to present it the way that we did it, right?

00:40:00.439 --> 00:40:04.040
And so I often try and get myself to think,

00:40:04.040 --> 00:40:06.120
to go through three rounds of like,

00:40:06.120 --> 00:40:08.120
okay, this is what makes sense to me.

00:40:08.120 --> 00:40:10.439
But now let me think again about my audience

00:40:10.439 --> 00:40:11.800
and what they wanna get from this.

00:40:11.800 --> 00:40:14.000
And what is the one thing

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:16.040
that I wanna make sure they take away?

00:40:16.040 --> 00:40:18.320
And then I change the way I present it.

00:40:18.320 --> 00:40:19.439
And then I do that again,

00:40:19.439 --> 00:40:22.000
because it's really hard to get out of that

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:24.360
kind of data science mindset into the,

00:40:25.280 --> 00:40:27.159
if I'm the CEO, I have to make a decision

00:40:27.159 --> 00:40:28.379
about this next week.

00:40:28.379 --> 00:40:31.159
I ask myself, if I were her,

00:40:31.159 --> 00:40:33.199
what would I do after seeing this?

00:40:33.199 --> 00:40:35.639
And am I getting that point across?

00:40:35.639 --> 00:40:36.899
Absolutely, thank you.

00:40:37.919 --> 00:40:40.800
David, I loved when you were kinda walking across the stage

00:40:40.800 --> 00:40:42.199
saying you're bringing your laptop

00:40:42.199 --> 00:40:45.520
from one meeting to the next across NASA.

00:40:45.520 --> 00:40:49.479
And I was wondering, how are you doing this today?

00:40:49.479 --> 00:40:51.739
Yeah, I mean, we've come a long way since that timeframe.

00:40:51.739 --> 00:40:53.560
So we've been able to implement

00:40:53.560 --> 00:40:55.879
a lot of different capabilities.

00:40:57.560 --> 00:40:59.879
COVID kinda helped a little bit, unfortunately.

00:40:59.879 --> 00:41:01.479
I hate to say that it helped,

00:41:01.479 --> 00:41:03.719
but it really puts some emphasis on the need

00:41:03.719 --> 00:41:05.520
for being able to share data more easily

00:41:05.520 --> 00:41:06.360
across the organization.

00:41:06.360 --> 00:41:07.840
So there was some funding that came up.

00:41:08.439 --> 00:41:11.120
We've had things for business intelligence.

00:41:11.120 --> 00:41:13.120
NASA actually had six Tableau servers

00:41:13.120 --> 00:41:14.399
across the agency at that time,

00:41:14.399 --> 00:41:15.959
so we consolidated them down to one

00:41:15.959 --> 00:41:17.979
and be able to share some business intelligence.

00:41:17.979 --> 00:41:19.479
But then we also have our POSIT server

00:41:19.479 --> 00:41:22.040
that allows us now to use our Connect server

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:23.419
to do some of the other things,

00:41:23.419 --> 00:41:25.080
whether it's a Shiny application,

00:41:25.080 --> 00:41:28.159
or created books, or wikis, or presentations,

00:41:28.159 --> 00:41:29.919
all of those things that go up to make it easier.

00:41:29.919 --> 00:41:32.239
So now we have one location

00:41:32.239 --> 00:41:35.239
where we created these portals, we call them,

00:41:35.239 --> 00:41:37.199
where they can go to that one landing page

00:41:37.239 --> 00:41:38.560
and connect to all these various

00:41:38.560 --> 00:41:40.600
different types of capabilities.

00:41:40.600 --> 00:41:41.879
Thank you.

00:41:41.879 --> 00:41:43.919
I see a lot of the questions starting to come in now,

00:41:43.919 --> 00:41:47.719
and one was, how can one-person teams

00:41:47.719 --> 00:41:52.719
advocate for IT and data science differentiation?

00:41:53.080 --> 00:41:55.879
I don't know if, Elaine, you wanna take that one?

00:41:55.879 --> 00:42:00.320
Yeah, I think when you're a one-person team,

00:42:00.320 --> 00:42:03.479
sometimes you have to do some of everything.

00:42:03.520 --> 00:42:07.320
And so I think it's about figuring out

00:42:07.320 --> 00:42:08.879
where to meet in the middle

00:42:08.879 --> 00:42:10.159
and helping people understand,

00:42:10.159 --> 00:42:13.439
like David was talking about, speaking the same language.

00:42:13.439 --> 00:42:15.000
So teams I've been in,

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:16.479
especially when we're getting started,

00:42:16.479 --> 00:42:19.219
we sometimes use tools kind of in that gap.

00:42:19.219 --> 00:42:22.120
We've used DBT as a way that we can think about

00:42:22.120 --> 00:42:24.719
structuring the data, and it's a little more friendly

00:42:24.719 --> 00:42:27.760
for people more on the engineering side

00:42:27.760 --> 00:42:29.320
to understand how that's coming in,

00:42:29.320 --> 00:42:31.600
and then we build out from there.

00:42:31.600 --> 00:42:35.560
So I think you kind of have to do whatever it takes

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:36.600
when you're just one person,

00:42:36.600 --> 00:42:39.840
but start to show people this is what this might look like,

00:42:39.840 --> 00:42:42.040
and these are the different steps in the process,

00:42:42.040 --> 00:42:44.840
even if you're doing more than one of them to begin with.

00:42:44.840 --> 00:42:46.320
Thank you.

00:42:46.320 --> 00:42:48.159
Did you have anything you wanted to add there?

00:42:48.159 --> 00:42:49.399
No, no, these are great answers.

00:42:49.399 --> 00:42:51.520
I mean, 20 years ago, it was probably me

00:42:51.520 --> 00:42:53.320
in a bottle of whiskey with the IT guy.

00:42:53.320 --> 00:42:55.320
You know, he'd say, let's talk.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:57.840
Okay.

00:42:57.959 --> 00:42:58.800
Okay.

00:42:59.919 --> 00:43:03.760
Another question, and I'll ask this to you first, David,

00:43:03.760 --> 00:43:07.040
is what if you have colleagues that are trying

00:43:07.040 --> 00:43:09.840
to make it difficult to get data

00:43:09.840 --> 00:43:12.120
for the sake of their job security?

00:43:12.120 --> 00:43:14.800
That's, unfortunately, that's common.

00:43:14.800 --> 00:43:16.040
I get a lot of that.

00:43:18.080 --> 00:43:22.120
I had this one teammate that needed some data

00:43:22.120 --> 00:43:25.199
from an organization, and she requested to go talk

00:43:25.199 --> 00:43:27.600
to the individuals, and when she got to the meeting,

00:43:28.360 --> 00:43:30.040
there were 17 other folks in that meeting

00:43:30.040 --> 00:43:33.280
questioning her, why do you need access to that data?

00:43:33.280 --> 00:43:35.199
And a lot of it came down,

00:43:35.199 --> 00:43:36.639
they were afraid they were gonna lose their jobs,

00:43:36.639 --> 00:43:38.040
and you really gotta show them,

00:43:38.040 --> 00:43:39.320
you had to find a way of showing them

00:43:39.320 --> 00:43:42.280
that it's not about taking away responsibility

00:43:42.280 --> 00:43:44.719
or taking away job duties, it's making it easier for them.

00:43:44.719 --> 00:43:46.439
How do we make this easier together?

00:43:46.439 --> 00:43:48.919
How do we share, how do I include you

00:43:48.919 --> 00:43:50.679
in that process, in that pipeline?

00:43:51.600 --> 00:43:55.560
But be honest, sometimes that job may become irrelevant,

00:43:55.560 --> 00:43:57.159
so what do I do to get you to change

00:43:57.719 --> 00:43:59.080
into a different role set, a different thing?

00:43:59.080 --> 00:44:01.239
So that's where you really need to work with managers.

00:44:01.239 --> 00:44:04.000
Okay, these things may change, how do we get this person

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:07.199
to still have a viable, meaningful job,

00:44:07.199 --> 00:44:09.120
but it may not be what they're doing right now

00:44:09.120 --> 00:44:10.679
because our pipelines have changed

00:44:10.679 --> 00:44:12.840
to kind of supersede all of that now.

00:44:14.080 --> 00:44:15.239
Thank you.

00:44:15.239 --> 00:44:18.840
Okay, one other question was, I'll ask this to you, Elaine.

00:44:18.840 --> 00:44:21.000
What advice do you have for those of us

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:25.560
trying to hand off processes we create to our stakeholders

00:44:25.600 --> 00:44:28.600
rather than maintaining them in perpetuity?

00:44:30.639 --> 00:44:32.520
That's an interesting question.

00:44:32.520 --> 00:44:35.560
So I think it depends a little on the situation

00:44:35.560 --> 00:44:39.360
of what you're trying to hand off and why.

00:44:39.360 --> 00:44:43.280
And sometimes I think there can be intermediate steps

00:44:43.280 --> 00:44:46.600
where you can do the handoff in different ways

00:44:46.600 --> 00:44:49.120
and maybe work your way back.

00:44:49.120 --> 00:44:52.280
One example someone was asking about yesterday

00:44:52.280 --> 00:44:55.840
was using pins to share data.

00:44:55.840 --> 00:44:58.080
And I was explaining a way that we've done this

00:44:58.080 --> 00:45:02.600
where we, in the process of running our Markdown files

00:45:02.600 --> 00:45:06.479
and Corda documents, we pin some things in Connect

00:45:06.479 --> 00:45:09.600
that are just CSVs that people can then take

00:45:09.600 --> 00:45:11.479
and do some of their own processes with.

00:45:11.479 --> 00:45:14.600
So even though at that point, the reports we're generating

00:45:14.600 --> 00:45:16.479
are still doing a lot of analysis,

00:45:16.479 --> 00:45:19.560
we're giving people a way into the middle of that process

00:45:19.560 --> 00:45:21.639
where they can start to participate

00:45:21.639 --> 00:45:22.959
and build on what we're doing

00:45:22.959 --> 00:45:25.520
and then work back to kind of where we started.

00:45:26.600 --> 00:45:27.840
Really?

00:45:27.840 --> 00:45:31.520
Okay, I think we have time for two more questions here.

00:45:32.879 --> 00:45:36.199
One of the questions was, we all love free stuff,

00:45:36.199 --> 00:45:38.600
but aside from hiring well,

00:45:38.600 --> 00:45:41.280
what have been the best investments you've made

00:45:41.280 --> 00:45:42.840
that cost serious money?

00:45:44.919 --> 00:45:46.120
Best investments?

00:45:46.120 --> 00:45:49.919
Well, the simple answer for me to start off with,

00:45:49.919 --> 00:45:52.320
we're not talking technology completely, it's the people.

00:45:52.320 --> 00:45:53.399
You've gotta have the right people

00:45:53.399 --> 00:45:55.000
and really invest heavily in your people,

00:45:55.000 --> 00:45:56.280
not only just who you're hiring,

00:45:56.280 --> 00:45:57.560
but the training they get

00:45:57.560 --> 00:45:59.919
and the ability to learn more of what they're doing.

00:45:59.919 --> 00:46:02.600
But if we're talking technology-wise,

00:46:02.600 --> 00:46:04.719
for me, I'm gonna have to say,

00:46:04.719 --> 00:46:08.120
because of the best bang for the buck

00:46:08.120 --> 00:46:09.199
that I've gotten so far,

00:46:09.199 --> 00:46:11.199
it's gonna have to be for the POSIT.

00:46:11.199 --> 00:46:13.919
And I'm not saying that because I'm at a POSIT conference.

00:46:13.919 --> 00:46:15.879
I know, somebody set up that question.

00:46:15.879 --> 00:46:16.719
I think.

00:46:16.719 --> 00:46:18.239
Thank you for asking that question.

00:46:18.639 --> 00:46:21.280
It allows me, for the money,

00:46:21.280 --> 00:46:23.800
for the number of users we can access,

00:46:23.800 --> 00:46:26.919
it allows me to do so many different things.

00:46:26.919 --> 00:46:29.239
With Tableau, and no offense Tableau,

00:46:29.239 --> 00:46:30.280
I can only do one thing,

00:46:30.280 --> 00:46:33.280
I can visualize some kind of business intelligence

00:46:33.280 --> 00:46:34.120
capability.

00:46:34.120 --> 00:46:36.679
If I need to send data back to my server,

00:46:36.679 --> 00:46:38.760
I can't do that from Tableau.

00:46:38.760 --> 00:46:41.560
So if I need a pipeline that's going back and forth,

00:46:41.560 --> 00:46:42.479
I need something different,

00:46:42.479 --> 00:46:44.520
and my investment in POSIT

00:46:44.520 --> 00:46:46.280
has definitely paid off a lot more.

00:46:47.280 --> 00:46:49.159
That's great to hear.

00:46:49.159 --> 00:46:50.679
Elaine, do you wanna add anything?

00:46:50.679 --> 00:46:51.600
Yeah, I agree.

00:46:51.600 --> 00:46:55.479
Definitely on the middle to end of the process,

00:46:55.479 --> 00:46:58.280
the POSIT Connect is versatile

00:46:58.280 --> 00:47:01.239
and has been really valuable to really get the value

00:47:01.239 --> 00:47:04.840
from the investment we've made in the data science humans.

00:47:04.840 --> 00:47:06.919
I think on the other end,

00:47:06.919 --> 00:47:09.560
another thing that's always been worth the investment

00:47:09.560 --> 00:47:11.520
is in data connectors.

00:47:11.520 --> 00:47:14.760
So ways, instead of having to go through engineering

00:47:14.800 --> 00:47:17.080
anytime, there's an out-of-the-box connector

00:47:17.080 --> 00:47:19.320
where you can buy something

00:47:19.320 --> 00:47:20.520
that someone else is maintaining

00:47:20.520 --> 00:47:21.760
and worrying about all the details,

00:47:21.760 --> 00:47:24.320
that it gets the data directly into your warehouse

00:47:24.320 --> 00:47:25.399
so you can take it from there.

00:47:25.399 --> 00:47:26.959
That's also a great investment.

00:47:27.919 --> 00:47:29.159
I'll just add one thing to that

00:47:29.159 --> 00:47:30.719
because something I've always thought about

00:47:30.719 --> 00:47:32.760
when I was starting off with R early on,

00:47:32.760 --> 00:47:34.560
is that there's like the App Store,

00:47:34.560 --> 00:47:36.560
there's a package for that.

00:47:36.560 --> 00:47:38.959
And there's always been that if I needed to do something new,

00:47:38.959 --> 00:47:40.159
if you figure out a way to do it,

00:47:40.159 --> 00:47:42.080
that I can definitely get a package

00:47:42.080 --> 00:47:43.520
in that open source capability

00:47:43.520 --> 00:47:44.959
along with commercializing

00:47:44.959 --> 00:47:47.080
and put it into an enterprise version.

00:47:47.080 --> 00:47:48.959
I know that I have a way of doing things,

00:47:48.959 --> 00:47:49.800
like Elaine was saying,

00:47:49.800 --> 00:47:51.719
I get those packages built somewhere else

00:47:51.719 --> 00:47:52.600
to do these things.

00:47:52.600 --> 00:47:54.159
So it's helped me a lot

00:47:54.159 --> 00:47:57.159
utilizing some of those tools and capabilities.

00:47:57.159 --> 00:47:58.679
Definitely.

00:47:58.679 --> 00:48:02.560
Okay, one question for you, Elaine,

00:48:02.560 --> 00:48:07.120
was going back to the framework that you showed us,

00:48:07.120 --> 00:48:09.959
do you have any tips for seeking out opportunities

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:14.360
when you aren't always invited to the business meetings?

00:48:14.360 --> 00:48:15.760
Yeah, this is a great question.

00:48:15.760 --> 00:48:18.560
And I believe I have asked this question

00:48:18.560 --> 00:48:21.000
of other people at previous Paws at Conferences.

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:24.199
How do I get in the room where all of this is happening?

00:48:25.360 --> 00:48:30.199
So I think you have to kind of give up initially

00:48:30.199 --> 00:48:33.080
on actually getting in the leadership meeting

00:48:33.080 --> 00:48:34.959
if you're not there already.

00:48:34.959 --> 00:48:37.199
And instead, make friends with people

00:48:37.199 --> 00:48:39.000
who are in those meetings

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:41.719
and ask good questions,

00:48:41.719 --> 00:48:44.919
pay attention in your company-wide meetings

00:48:44.919 --> 00:48:47.080
and think about what's going on with the business

00:48:47.080 --> 00:48:48.919
or the organization that you're part of

00:48:48.919 --> 00:48:51.520
and put yourself in the head of those leaders

00:48:51.520 --> 00:48:52.840
and what they care about.

00:48:52.840 --> 00:48:54.919
And then people usually are not trying

00:48:54.919 --> 00:48:56.879
to keep you from knowing things.

00:48:56.879 --> 00:48:58.760
So I think, yeah, asking a lot of questions,

00:48:58.760 --> 00:48:59.840
going to lunch with people,

00:48:59.840 --> 00:49:01.000
setting up Zoom meetings

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:04.719
and just really being heads up about thinking about

00:49:04.719 --> 00:49:07.919
what they're thinking about and how you can address it.

00:49:07.919 --> 00:49:09.959
One thing I'd like to add to that is,

00:49:09.959 --> 00:49:11.639
at least in what I've seen at NASA,

00:49:11.639 --> 00:49:15.719
is find a mentor that knows it's connected, it's networked,

00:49:15.719 --> 00:49:17.120
somebody that you can talk to,

00:49:17.120 --> 00:49:19.159
utilize and ask them those questions.

00:49:19.159 --> 00:49:20.000
You know, how do I do this?

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:21.239
How do I connect?

00:49:21.239 --> 00:49:22.959
Many times they'll make the introductions

00:49:22.959 --> 00:49:24.199
and make the connections for you

00:49:24.199 --> 00:49:27.239
or they know who they can do that or what they can do.

00:49:27.239 --> 00:49:29.000
So start reaching out

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:32.560
because those type of people want to share their information.

00:49:32.560 --> 00:49:33.800
They want to share their knowledge.

00:49:33.800 --> 00:49:36.320
So ask them, you'll be surprised how many people say,

00:49:36.399 --> 00:49:38.280
yes, I'll mentor you on these things.

00:49:38.280 --> 00:49:39.760
Yep.

00:49:39.760 --> 00:49:42.080
Thank you both so much.

00:49:42.080 --> 00:49:45.439
There are so many amazing questions still left in Slido.

00:49:45.439 --> 00:49:49.199
And so I have to use this opportunity to also say,

00:49:49.199 --> 00:49:53.159
like, we get to talk about things like this every Thursday

00:49:53.159 --> 00:49:54.800
at the Data Science Hangout.

00:49:54.800 --> 00:49:58.199
If anybody wants to join us virtually there,

00:49:58.199 --> 00:50:00.639
we've had conversations with Elaine and David there,

00:50:00.639 --> 00:50:03.679
but every week we have a different featured leader

00:50:03.679 --> 00:50:05.399
who joins us from the community.

00:50:05.399 --> 00:50:09.000
So I would love to have you all join us there.

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:11.719
But with that, I know we have to get out to our break.

00:50:11.719 --> 00:50:13.399
I want you to be able to grab some coffee,

00:50:13.399 --> 00:50:15.800
stretch your legs, check out the lounge

00:50:15.800 --> 00:50:19.040
before our next keynote back here at 1030.

00:50:19.040 --> 00:50:20.959
But thank you so much, Elaine and David,

00:50:20.959 --> 00:50:21.800
for your presentation.

00:50:21.800 --> 00:50:22.639
Thank you.

00:50:22.639 --> 00:50:23.479
Thank you.

